1_how_to_make_a_heatmap

Making heatmap is an essential skill for any computational biologist.

load the libraries

library(ComplexHeatmap)

library(gofigR)
enable(TRUE)
## Analysis name: 01_how_to_make_a_heatmap.Rmd

make dummy data

h1 <- c(10,20,10,20,10,20,10,20)
h2 <- c(20,10,20,10,20,10,20,10)

l1 <- c(1,3,1,3,1,3,1,3)
l2 <- c(3,1,3,1,3,1,3,1)

mat <- rbind(h1,h2,l1,l2)
colnames(mat)<- paste0("timepoint_", 1:8)
mat
##    timepoint_1 timepoint_2 timepoint_3 timepoint_4 timepoint_5 timepoint_6
## h1          10          20          10          20          10          20
## h2          20          10          20          10          20          10
## l1           1           3           1           3           1           3
## l2           3           1           3           1           3           1
##    timepoint_7 timepoint_8
## h1          10          20
## h2          20          10
## l1           1           3
## l2           3           1

visualize the data

publish_base({
  par(mfrow =c(1,1), mar=c(4,4,1,1))
  plot(1:8,rep(0,8), ylim=c(0,35), pch="", xlab="Time", ylab="Gene Expression")
  
  for (i in 1:nrow(mat)) {
  lines(1:8,mat[i,], lwd=3, col=i)
  }
  
  legend(1,35,rownames(mat), 1:4, cex=0.7)
}, "Gene Expression")

Making a heatmap is easy!

publish(Heatmap(mat, cluster_columns = FALSE))
## Warning in publish(Heatmap(mat, cluster_columns = FALSE)): Your figure lacks a
## name and will be published as Anonymous Figure.

quantile(mat, c(0, 0.1,0.5, 0.9))
##   0%  10%  50%  90% 
##  1.0  1.0  6.5 20.0

change color mapping

col_fun<- circlize::colorRamp2(c(0, 3, 20), c("blue", "white", "red"))

publish(Heatmap(mat, cluster_columns = FALSE, col = col_fun))
## Warning in publish(Heatmap(mat, cluster_columns = FALSE, col = col_fun)): Your
## figure lacks a name and will be published as Anonymous Figure.

outlier

mat2<- mat
mat2[1,1]<- 1000

publish(Heatmap(mat2, cluster_columns = FALSE))
## Warning in publish(Heatmap(mat2, cluster_columns = FALSE)): Your figure lacks a
## name and will be published as Anonymous Figure.

publish(Heatmap(mat2, cluster_columns = FALSE, col = col_fun))
## Warning in publish(Heatmap(mat2, cluster_columns = FALSE, col = col_fun)): Your
## figure lacks a name and will be published as Anonymous Figure.

Let’s scale the data/gene expression level across columns (time points) first

scaled_mat<- t(scale(t(mat)))


?Heatmap
publish(Heatmap(scaled_mat, cluster_columns = FALSE))
## Warning in publish(Heatmap(scaled_mat, cluster_columns = FALSE)): Your figure
## lacks a name and will be published as Anonymous Figure.

Note, after scaling, h1 and l1 are close to each other!

understand clustering?

define distances

?dist

d<- dist(mat)

d
##           h1        h2        l1
## h2 28.284271                    
## l1 38.470768 40.496913          
## l2 40.496913 38.470768  5.656854
?hclust

hclust(d)
## 
## Call:
## hclust(d = d)
## 
## Cluster method   : complete 
## Distance         : euclidean 
## Number of objects: 4
publish_base(plot(hclust(d)))
## Warning in publish(asgg, ...): Your figure lacks a name and will be published
## as Anonymous Figure.

After scaling

d2<- dist(scaled_mat)

publish_base(plot(hclust(d2)))
## Warning in publish(asgg, ...): Your figure lacks a name and will be published
## as Anonymous Figure.

Key takeaways: 1. color mapping is critical 2. scaling is critical 3. making heatmap is easy, but better to understand the details.
